  "prompt": "Do US presidents get bodyguard protection after they have left the office?",
  "response": "Yes, former U.S. presidents continue to receive Secret Service protection after leaving office, though the duration and extent of that protection have evolved over time.\n\n### **Historical Context**\n\nOriginally, the **Former Presidents Act of 1958** provided lifetime Secret Service protection to former presidents and their spouses. This law recognized the unique stature and potential security needs of individuals who had held the highest office in the United States.\n\n### **Changes in Protection Duration**\n\nIn **2013**, Congress passed the **Former Presidents Protection Act**, which significantly altered the scope of Secret Service protection for former presidents:\n\n- **Duration of Protection:** Instead of lifetime protection, former presidents are now entitled to Secret Service protection for **10 years** following the end of their presidency.\n  \n- **Spousal Protection:** The lifetime protection for spouses of former presidents remains unchanged. This means that while the former president's personal protection ends after ten years, their spouse continues to receive lifetime protection.\n\n### **Extension Beyond Ten Years**\n\nAfter the initial ten-year period, former presidents **do not automatically continue to receive Secret Service protection**. However, extension of protection beyond ten years is possible under certain circumstances:\n\n- **Continued Threats:** If a former president faces credible and ongoing security threats, Congress may decide to extend their Secret Service protection.\n  \n- **Legislative Action:** Any extension beyond the standard ten-year period would require new legislation passed by Congress and signed into law by the President.\n\n### **Eligibility for Protection**\n\nThe Secret Service\u2019s protective mission includes ensuring the safety of former presidents due to their continued prominence and potential as targets. Factors influencing the level of protection include:\n\n- **Public Visibility:** Engagements, public appearances, and continued public influence can affect the need for ongoing protection.\n  \n- **Threat Assessments:** Continuous evaluation of potential threats determines whether extended protection is necessary.\n\n### **Notable Considerations**\n\n- **Presidential Families:** While former presidents receive protection, this does not automatically extend to all family members. Typically, only the spouse is covered unless specific threats justify protection of other family members.\n\n- **Ex-Presidents Before 1950s:** Some early former presidents might have different or additional protections based on when they served and the prevailing laws during their time.\n\n### **Conclusion**\n\nIn summary, former U.S. presidents receive Secret Service protection for ten years following their presidency, with the possibility of extension under certain conditions. Their spouses, however, continue to receive lifetime protection. This framework balances the need for security with legislative intent to limit the scope of Secret Service responsibilities over time.",
